  "prompt": "What is the shelf life of ammo? Five years ago I bought bulk ammo and I'm wondering about its reliability.",
  "response": "The shelf life of ammunition depends on several factors, including storage conditions:\n\n1. Proper storage conditions:\n- Cool, dry environment\n- Low humidity\n- Away from direct sunlight\n- Sealed in original packaging or airtight container\n\n2. Typical ammunition shelf life:\n- Factory ammunition: 10-25 years if stored properly\n- Military surplus: 50+ years in some cases\n- Handloaded/reloaded ammo: 5-10 years\n\n3. Signs of potential degradation:\n- Corrosion on brass/primer\n- Discoloration\n- Moisture damage\n- Primer seal looks compromised\n\n4. Best practices:\n- Rotate stock periodically\n- Store in climate-controlled area\n- Check ammunition visually before use\n- Test fire a few rounds if uncertain\n\nIf your ammo has been stored in good conditions, it's likely still reliable. However, for critical use (self-defense, hunting), it's recommended to replace older ammunition or have it professionally inspected.\n\nNote: While old ammunition might still fire, reliability and performance can decrease over time.",
